Cairn-Mother Retha An was a post-Conclave pass witness active in the Cinderteeth route network after the Spirebound Conclave's collapse.
She is credited in scattered Kiess and Kowloon archival references with preserving non-state route names during map-loss periods following Conclave dissolution.
Both sets of records describe her as mountain-tongue born — a phrase indicating Ventspeaker-adjacent cultural origin and inherited interpretive tradition.
Her title Cairn-Mother denotes a specific role: a witness who maintains cairn-station legal identity when no state authority is present to certify it.
In the post-Conclave period, Cinderteeth passes lost official survey certification as the Conclave's records were destroyed, sealed, or contested.
Retha An is credited with maintaining passage rights for at least four major saddle crossings by personally attesting their continuity of use.
Her attestation method drew on Ventspeaker oral practice: she encoded route information in rhythmic chants that preserved distance, hazard, and direction.
This placed her at the intersection of two knowledge systems: mountain-tradition oral route memory and emerging caravan-law witness certification.
Kiess cites her as a precedent case in frontier witness doctrine: an individual can hold legal continuity of a route if no institution remains to hold it.
Her pass-names, including at least two Ridgekin-derived terms she preserved, appear in Kiess route law as the oldest non-institutional geographic certifications.
Kowloon's northern survey records acknowledge her work indirectly through route entries that predate formal Kowloon survey activity in the passes.
She is a figure without a burial record, estate file, or descendant claim. Her legal existence is entirely documentary.

